03331nam a22004575i 9780773564008DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19831983xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735640087 a10.1515/97807735640082doi  a(DE-B1597)657127  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aB785.C364bS36 1983eb 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1921 aSchmitt, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJohn Case and Aristotelianism in Renaissance England /cCharles Schmitt. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1983] 4c©1983  a1 online resource (321 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tAristotelianism in England -- tThe Life and Works of John Case -- tJohn Case and His Intellectual Milieu -- tCase’s Eclectic Aristotelianism and Its Historical Context -- tJohn Case on Art and Nature -- tConclusion -- tLogic Books Printed in England before 1620 -- tJohn Case’s Will -- tJohn Case’s Letters -- tThe Apologia Academiarum -- tPrefatory Letters and Liminary Verses to Case’s Works -- tThe Title Page of Lapis Philosophicus -- tTabula from LP',195 -- tThe Authorship of The Praise of Musicke -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDr. Schmitt shows that Case was heir to both the traditions of scholastic interpretation of Aristotle and the new humanistic currents, that his Aristotelianism was strongly eclectic, and that he drew heavily upon Renaissance Neoplatonic and other intellectual traditions in compiling well-rounded philosophical manuals adapted to his age. Schmitt argues that, even though Case was the prime representative of peripatetic thought during Elizabeth's reign, he forged strong links with leading figures in such areas of English culture as drama, literature, art, and music, as well as with important ecclesiastical and political figures. He also contends that Aristotelian philosophy had a much more central position in England than has been previously admitted. Case's position in the scholastic revival which marked late sixteenth- and early seventeenth-century English intellectual life is charted, and the historical reality of this revival is firmly established.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356400840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564008423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564008/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles